description.narrative: (Ethiopia): .Ethiopia's Developing Regional States have dispersed, mobile populations, weak health infrastructure and Ethiopia's worst health indicators. Prone to frequent and recurrent drought, many districts are categorized as hotspots, with food insecurity, malnutrition and disease outbreaks. With FY 2020 funds, Transform: Health in Developing Regions (THDR) will build the capacity of local health providers and administrators, using targeted training, mentorship, joint supervision, and health system support to deliver PHC services in order to make durable improvements in the health status of these vulnerable communities. The activity supports community engagement interventions to increase demand for appropriate care-seeking, critical during and following the COVID-19 pandemic to ensure continuity of essential services such as immunizations, voluntary family planning, and maternal, newborn and child health services. USAID will support: 1) Delivery of priority, high-impact quality PHC services, particularly for family planning and maternal, newborn, and child health; 2) Capacity building of four regional health bureaus and sub-regional structures in targeted districts; 3) Capacity building to improve health education and communication; and 4) Implementation research to test and scale successful models...This activity applies learning from similar USAID investments in the agrarian regions, adapting as required to meet needs of pastoral and agro-pastoralist communities. Efforts to strengthen district level ability to plan, finance, and manage higher standards of health service delivery contributes to Ethiopia's self-reliance. THDR will also support health sector strategic and resource planning skills, and build the capacity to generate, analyze, and apply data in real time. These core competencies are vital as Ethiopia tries to optimize limited resources despite immense needs, particularly in those regions that face recurrent drought and disease outbreaks. .. .
